I think a lot about how the Millennials were the last generation to build relationships with artists without being expected to critically view them.
We grew up in an age of media abundance, with a collective awareness of pop culture that no longer exists.
We could engage with things without having to ponder where they came from, as it was not as easy to trace those origins back then.
We did not question the platform we placed them on. These parasocial relationships were so significant and influenced our lives.
This is why we have such a strong inclination towards nostalgia.
As "The Office" was still on, my friends and I ordered pizza every Thursday and watched the series together.
This was very different from today's streaming, where 12 episodes come out at once and everyone watches whenever they feel like it and posts on social media with "spoiler warnings" or discusses them in closed groups.
Subconsciously, we yearn for this universal community that used to dominate everything.
That's why so many of us still watch series like "The Office" or films like "Anchorman", which featured so many one-liners that would be memes today.
We had brought these jokes along and assumed that most people would understand them.
Today, it is no longer safe to assume that everyone knows something, even if it spreads massively virally.
There is too much out there, and there is no way to systematize it. Can we possibly get out of this oversaturation?
We are trapped in a vicious cycle, constantly discovering new content only to realize that the artist is greedy or a hypocrite.
Therefore, we must cling to our nostalgia while also accepting that the people who created the works we liked could also have made significant mistakes.
We approach parasocial relationships with greater caution.
